  "prompt": "Where can I get a place to stay in goa for a low budget?",
  "response": "Goa offers a lot of budget-friendly accommodation options. Here's a breakdown of places you can look, with some specific examples and tips:\n\n**1. Hostels:**\n\n*   **Why they're great:** By far the cheapest option.  You'll be in a dorm room, often with shared bathrooms.  Great for meeting other travelers.\n*   **Where to find them:**\n    *   **Hostelworld.com:**  A very popular site specifically for hostels.  Read reviews carefully!\n    *   **Booking.com:**  While known for hotels, they also list hostels.\n    *   **Google Maps:** Search \"hostels in [Goa location]\" (e.g., \"hostels in Anjuna\")\n*   **Key Locations:**\n    *   **Anjuna & Vagator:** Popular with backpackers, lots of party vibes.  Expect it to be a bit noisier.\n    *   **Arambol:** More laid-back, yogi/spiritual vibe.  Generally cheaper than Anjuna/Vagator.\n    *   **Palolem:**  South Goa, more relaxed, beautiful beach.  Hostels may be slightly pricier than in the north, but still budget-friendly.\n*   **Examples (check current prices online as they fluctuate):**\n    *   **Anjuna:** Jungle by thehostelcrowd, Dreams Hostel Anjuna, Roadhouse Hostels Anjuna\n    *   **Vagator:** That Crazy Hostel Vagator, Pappi Chulo\n    *   **Arambol:** The Lazy Dog, Jugaad Hostel Arambol\n    *   **Palolem:** Whoopers Hostel Palolem, Backpacker Panda Palolem\n\n**2. Guesthouses & Budget Hotels:**\n\n*   **Why they're great:** You get a private room (usually with an attached bathroom), often for a reasonable price.\n*   **Where to find them:**\n    *   **Booking.com:**  Filter by price and guest rating.\n    *   **Agoda.com:** Another good option for hotels and guesthouses.\n    *   **MakeMyTrip, Goibibo, Yatra:**  Popular Indian travel sites, often have deals.\n    *   **Airbnb:**  Can find some great deals, especially for longer stays.  Look for \"private rooms\" within homes.\n    *   **Walk-ins:**  During the off-season (monsoon season, roughly June to September), you can often find good deals by walking around and asking at guesthouses. Be prepared to haggle!\n*   **Key Locations:**\n    *   **Calangute & Baga:**  Very touristy, so lots of options, but can be crowded. Prices may be slightly higher than other areas.\n    *   **Candolim:**  Slightly more upscale than Calangute/Baga, but still has budget options.\n    *   **Morjim:**  North Goa, more relaxed, known for its Russian influence.\n    *   **Agonda:** South Goa, quiet and beautiful beach.\n*   **Examples (check current prices online as they fluctuate):**\n    *   **Calangute/Baga:**  Lobos Beach Resort, Casa Aguada, Baga Deck Holiday Homes (some rooms might fit your budget).\n    *   **Candolim:** Santana Beach Resort (might have budget-friendly rooms), Sea Shell Suites & Villas (look for their smaller rooms).\n    *   **Morjim:**  Montego Bay Beach Village (some cottages might be affordable), Larisa Beach Resort Morjim (check for deals).\n    *   **Agonda:**  Agonda White Sand, Simrose\n\n**3. Homestays:**\n\n*   **Why they're great:**  A more immersive experience, often with home-cooked meals.  Can be very budget-friendly.\n*   **Where to find them:**\n    *   **Airbnb:**  The best place to find homestays. Look for \"private rooms\" or even entire apartments.\n    *   **Homestay.com:** Specializes in homestays.\n*   **Key Locations:**\n    *   Homestays are available throughout Goa. Consider what you want to do (beaches, nightlife, etc.) when choosing a location.\n\n**4. Beach Huts (Seasonal):**\n\n*   **Why they're great:**  Right on the beach!  Very basic, but a unique experience.  Generally only available during the tourist season (October to May).\n*   **Where to find them:**\n    *   **Palolem, Agonda, Arambol:** These beaches are known for their beach huts.  You'll likely need to book in advance during peak season.\n    *   **Walk-ins:**  Sometimes you can find available huts by walking along the beach.\n*   **Important Considerations:**\n    *   Basic amenities.  Don't expect luxury.\n    *   Can be noisy, especially if close to shacks with music.\n    *   Limited privacy.\n\n**Tips for Finding the Best Deals:**\n\n*   **Travel during the off-season (Monsoon):**  Prices are significantly lower, but be prepared for rain.  Many businesses close down during the monsoon.\n*   **Book in advance (especially during peak season):** This gives you more options and can sometimes lead to early-bird discounts.\n*   **Be flexible with location:** Staying a bit further from the main beaches can save you money.\n*   **Read reviews carefully:**  Pay attention to what other travelers say about cleanliness, location, and value for money.\n*   **Haggle (if appropriate):**  Especially if you're staying for a longer period or during the off-season.\n*   **Consider cooking some of your own meals:** Eating out can be expensive.  Look for accommodations with kitchen facilities.\n*   **Look for deals and promotions:** Many websites and accommodations offer special discounts.\n*   **Use local transportation:**  Renting a scooter is a popular (and cheap) way to get around, but be careful on the roads.  Buses are also a budget-friendly option.\n*   **Network:** Talk to other travelers. They might have good recommendations or leads on hidden gems.\n\nTo help me give you even more specific recommendations, tell me:\n\n*   **When are you planning to travel?** (This significantly impacts prices)\n*   **What kind of experience are you looking for?** (Party scene, quiet relaxation, cultural immersion, etc.)\n*   **Which part of Goa are you most interested in?** (North, South, Central)\n*   **What's your absolute maximum budget per night?** (In Indian Rupees or your local currency)\n\nGood luck with your search!  Goa is an amazing place, and you can definitely have a great time on a budget.\n",
